<xml>
    <metadata><title>Ballad of Booker T.</title>, by <author>Langston Hughes</author>, <date
            when="1941-06-01">June 1, 1941</date> Citation: <collection>Drafts of Langston Hughes's
            poem "Ballad of Booker T.</collection>," <writeDate st="1941-5-30" end="1941-06-01">30
            May–1 June 1941</writeDate>. <collection>(Langston Hughes Collection)</collection>
        <archive group="Maunsrcipt Division" inst="Library of Congress" location="Washington, D.C."
            >Manuscript Division, Library of Congress, Washington, D.C.</archive></metadata>
    <heading type="source"><title trait="caps">BALLAD OF BOOKER T.</title> by <author>Langston
            Hughes</author></heading>
    <poem>
        <st num="1">
            <ln>Booker T.</ln>
            <I/>
            <!--I. Booker Taliaferro Washington was an author and educator born in the mid-19th century. He's most well known for his advancement of the African-American community, and opening a school.-->
            <ln rym="an">Was a practical man.</ln>
            <ln>He said, Till the soil</ln>
            <ln rym="an">And learn from the land.</ln>
            <II/>
            <!--II. Hughes is referring to Washington's advocacy of land work, touching on similar quotes of his like: "No race can prosper till it learns that there is as much dignity in tilling a field as in writing a poem."-->
            <ln>Let down your <stpAffect>bucket</stpAffect></ln>
            <ln rym="ar">Where you are.</ln>
            <ln>Your fate is <stpAffect>here</stpAffect></ln>
            <a/>
            <!--a. Right around this point on the physical document, a circular, red stamp with an eagle design (from the U.S. Library of Congress) is located, cutting into about 5 lines of text.-->
            <ln rym="ar">And not afar.</ln>
        </st>
        <st num="2">
            <ln>To help <stpAffect>yourself</stpAffect></ln>
            <ln rym="an">And your fellow <stpAffect>man</stpAffect>,</ln>
            <ln>Train your head,</ln>
            <ln rym="an">Your heart, <unL>and your hand.</unL></ln>
            <ln>For smartness alone's</ln>
            <ln rym="eet">Surely not meet—</ln>
            <ln>If you haven't at the same time</ln>
            <ln rym="eet">Got something to eat.</ln>
        </st>
        <st num="3">
            <ln>Thus at Tuskegee</ln>
            <III/>
            <!--III. Tuskegee, Alabama is where Washington opened his school (in 1881), Tuskegee University.-->
            <ln rym="ool">He built a school</ln>
            <ln>With book-learning there</ln>
            <ln rym="ool">And the workman's tool.</ln>
            <ln>He started out</ln>
            <ln rym="ay">In a simple way—</ln>
            <ln>For yesterday </ln>
            <ln rym="ay">Was <unL>not</unL>today.</ln>
        </st>
        <st num="4">
            <ln>Sometimes he had</ln>
            <ln rym="awk">Compromise in his talk—</ln>
            <ln>For a man must crawl</ln>
            <ln rym="awk">Before he can walk—</ln>
            <ln rym="ive">And in Alabama in '85</ln>
            <ln>A joker was lucky</ln>
            <ln rym="ive">To be alive.</ln>
        </st>
        <st num="5">
            <ln>But Booker T.</ln>
            <ln rym="ool">Was nobody's fool:</ln>
            <ln>You may carve a dream</ln>
            <ln rym="ool">With an humble tool.</ln>
            <ln>The tallest tower</ln>
            <ln rym="own">Can tumble down</ln>
            <ln>If it be not rooted</ln>
            <ln rym="own">In solid ground.</ln>
        </st>
        <st num="6"><ln>So, being a far-seeing</ln>
            <ln rym="an">Practical man,</ln>
            <ln>He said, Train your head,</ln>
            <ln rym="an">Your heart, <unL>and your hand</unL>.</ln>
            <ln>Your fate is here</ln>
            <ln rym="ar">And not afar,</ln>
            <ln>So let down your bucket</ln><IV/>
            <!--IV. Hughes is alluding to Washington's own speech about the Atlanta Compromise, which called for the resistance to discrimination ("cast your bucket down").-->
            <ln rym="ar">Where you are.</ln>
        </st>
    </poem>
    <author trait="signature">LANGSTON HUGHES</author>
    <b/>
    <!--b. Langston Hughes' physical signature is present, with the bold, black pen covering up over most of the bottom information (sigAffect).-->
